The reason we use `std::move` in the example is due to how `std::unique_ptr` manages ownership. `std::unique_ptr` enforces unique ownership of the managed object, meaning that a resource managed by a `std::unique_ptr` instance can be owned by only one `std::unique_ptr` instance at a time. This unique ownership model is enforced by deleting the copy constructor and copy assignment operator of `std::unique_ptr`, making it impossible to accidentally or implicitly copy a `std::unique_ptr`.

When you're passing a `std::unique_ptr` to a function (or a constructor, in this case) by value and you want to transfer ownership to that function (or constructor), you must use `std::move`. The `std::move` function casts its argument to an r-value reference, enabling the move constructor or move assignment operator of the receiving object (if they are defined), transferring the resource's ownership without copying it. Without `std::move`, you're attempting to copy the `std::unique_ptr`, which, as described, is not allowed.

So, in your suggested code:

```cpp
std::unique_ptr<Rect> srcRect = std::make_unique<Rect>(args…);
std::unique_ptr<Rect> dstRect = std::make_unique<Rect>(args…);
std::unique_ptr<Transform> transform = std::make_unique<Transform>(args…);

Texture texture(renderer, surface, filename, srcRect, dstRect, transform);
```

This would result in a compilation error because you're trying to copy `std::unique_ptr` instances. The compiler would reject these calls because the copy constructor of `std::unique_ptr` is deleted to maintain unique ownership semantics.

Therefore, when the intention is to transfer the ownership of the resource managed by a `std::unique_ptr` to another function or constructor, using `std::move` is necessary. This effectively signals to the compiler and to anyone reading the code that ownership of the resource is being transferred:

```cpp
Texture texture(renderer, surface, filename, std::move(srcRect), std::move(dstRect), std::move(transform));
```

And in the constructor's initialization list:

```cpp
Texture::Texture(...) : texture(nullptr, &SDL_DestroyTexture), sourceRect(std::move(srcRect)), destinationRect(std::move(dstRect)), transform(std::move(transform)) { /* ... */ }
```

This ensures that the `Texture` instance takes over the ownership of the `Rect` and `Transform` instances, while the original `std::unique_ptr` instances (`srcRect`, `dstRect`, and `transform`) in the caller site become empty (i.e., they no longer own or manage any resource).

